#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:10
msgid "PREREQUISITES: None"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:17
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"DESCRIPTION:\n"
"    GRUB2 is the next generation of GNU GRUB. The version, as of this date, "
"\n"
"    is grub-1.97~beta2.  This is a very workable system for most LFS \n"
"    installations and can be built and run on several architectures\n"
"    including i386, powerpc, and x86_64.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:19
msgid "REFERENCES: http://grub.enbug.org/"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:22
msgid "HINT:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:25
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Installing GRUB2:\n"
"   wget ftp://alpha.gnu.org/gnu/grub/grub-1.97~beta3.tar.gz\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:27
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   The md5sum is 542917012de4d2e47241bdffb67bedef and the file size is "
"1.3Mb.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:30
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   tar -xf grub-1.97~beta3.tar.gz\n"
"   cd grub-1.97~beta3\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:34
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   ./configure --prefix=/usr --sysconfdir=/etc --disable-largefile \\\n"
"          --disable-grub-emu  --disable-grub-emu-usb  --disable-grub-fstest "
"\\\n"
"          --disable-efiemu\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:37
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   The --disable switches just minimze what is built by disabling features\n"
"   and testing programs not really needed for LFS.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:40
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   make\n"
"   sudo make install\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:42
#, no-wrap
msgid "   The install adds the following programs and directories:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:45
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   /usr/bin:\n"
"   grub-editenv  grub-mkelfimage  grub-mkfont  grub-mkimage  grub-mkrescue\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:48
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   /usr/sbin:\n"
"   grub-dumpbios  grub-install  grub-mkconfig  grub-mkdevicemap  grub-probe  "
"grub-setup\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:51
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   /etc/grub.d:\n"
"   00_header  10_linux  30_os-prober  40_custom  README\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:54
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   /usr/include/:\n"
"   grub/  multiboot.h  multiboot2.h\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:56
#, no-wrap
msgid "   /usr/lib/grub:  Many supporting files\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:60
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   No man pages are installed unless you have the help2man program "
"installed.  \n"
"   To get minimal help, use --help on each executable program.  There are "
"no\n"
"   info pages yet available.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:62
msgid "Configuring GRUB2:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:66
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   When setting up the boot directory on LFS, I highly recommend using a "
"separate\n"
"   partition for /boot.  That way each build, whether LFS or some commercial "
"distro,\n"
"   can access the same boot files and access can be made from any booted "
"system.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:70
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   I use /dev/sda1 and create the boot partition as 100Mb.  That leaves "
"lots\n"
"   of room for new kernels, but does not take up much space from the large "
"\n"
"   disk drives generally in use today.  \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:72
#, no-wrap
msgid "   The rest of this hint assumes a separately mounted boot partition:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:74
#, no-wrap
msgid "   /dev/sda1 on /boot type ext3 (rw)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:76
#, no-wrap
msgid "   Step 1.  As root, install the GRUB2 files into /boot/grub\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:78
#, no-wrap
msgid "   grub-install --grub-setup=/bin/true /dev/sda\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:83
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   This step creates the core.img file needed to boot, but does not install "
"it\n"
"   into the master boot record (MBR).  If the --grub-setup=/bin/true "
"switch\n"
"   is not set, the MBR *will* be updated.  That is probably not what you "
"want\n"
"   until you have tested the installation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:88
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   This step populates /boot/grub/ with many files.  GRUB2 utilizes a "
"system\n"
"   of modules to extend basic functionality.  Right now there are 125 "
"modules \n"
"   installed.  There are also a few other files with extentions of .img, "
".map,\n"
"   .o, and .lst.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:90
#, no-wrap
msgid "   Step2.  As root, generate /boot/grub/grub.cfg\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:92
#, no-wrap
msgid "   grub-mkconfig -o /boot/grub/grub.cfg\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:99
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   This program uses the scripts in /etc/grub.d/ to generate the "
"configuruation\n"
"   file.  By default, it looks for files with the naming convention of\n"
"   vmlinu[xz]-*.  My naming conventions for kernels is different.  For\n"
"   instance, one kernel is named linux-2.6.30.2-lfs65.  I had to modify line "
"64\n"
"   of /etc/grub.d/10_linux to add /boot/linux* to the list of filenames\n"
"   searched.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:101
#, no-wrap
msgid "   The entries in /boot/grub/grub.cfg look like:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:108
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   menuentry \"GNU/Linux, Linux 2.6.30.2-lfs65\" {\n"
"      insmod ext2\n"
"      set root=(hd0,1)\n"
"      #search --no-floppy --fs-uuid --set "
"2ae9c39c-c1ee-4006-80af-5a3d41f1255c\n"
"      linux /linux-2.6.30.2-lfs65 root=/dev/sda5 ro\n"
"   }\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:113
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   Note that I commented out the search line above because it was assuming "
"the\n"
"   wrong root partition.  The linux line specifies the / directory because\n"
"   the /boot directory is mounted on a separate partition and the files "
"are\n"
"   relative to the unmounted partition.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:117
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   One other comment is that GRUB2 uses partition numbers relative to 1.  "
"Legacy \n"
"   GRUB used partitions relative to 0.  Therefore the line using (hd0,1) "
"refers\n"
"   to /dev/sda1.  \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:119
#, no-wrap
msgid "   Step 3.  Test the configuration.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:122
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   The core image of GRUB 2 is also a Multiboot kernel, so you can load "
"GRUB2 \n"
"   by GRUB Legacy:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:128
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   /sbin/reboot\n"
"   ...\n"
"   grub> root (hd0,0)\n"
"   grub> kernel /boot/grub/core.img\n"
"   grub> boot\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:132
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   At this point the GRUB2 prompt will appear (very similar to GRUB Legacy) "
"and\n"
"   you can explore the interface or boot to one of the systems in the "
"grub.cfg \n"
"   file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:134
#, no-wrap
msgid "   Step 4.  As root, update the Master Boot Record\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:136
#, no-wrap
msgid "   grub-setup\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:143
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"   This program uses the following defaults:\n"
"   boot image  - boot.img\n"
"   core image  - core.img\n"
"   directory   - /boot/grub\n"
"   device map  - device.map\n"
"   root device - guessed\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/grub2.txt:145
#, no-wrap
msgid "   The defaults are generally OK for an LFS sytem.\n"
msgstr ""

